From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|wæs|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|was|lang=en}}, (identical to Low German {{term|was|lang=nds}}, cognate with German {{term|war|lang=de}}) < {{proto|Indo-European|h₂wes-|to reside|lang=en}}. The paradigm of "to be" has been since the time of Proto-Germanic a synthesis of three originally distinct verb stems. The infinitive form {{term|be|lang=en}} is from {{proto|Indo-European|bʰew-|to become|lang=}}. The words {{term|is|lang=en}} and {{term|are|lang=en}} are both derived from {{proto|Indo-European|h₁es-|to be|lang=}}. Lastly, the past forms starting with ''w-'' such as ''was'' and {{term|were|lang=en}} are from {{proto|Indo-European|h₂wes-|to reside|lang=}}.

